Tammy and Deb,
After reading Blaise=92s email, a few of his points stood out quite clearly=
 =97 particularly his comments around the financial pressure clinics are fa=
cing, the risks associated with a failure to act, and the potential for cat=
astrophic consequences if clinics allow financial drift to continue uncheck=
ed. His message was a strong reminder that maintaining financial sustainabi=
lity requires actively managing the operational factors that quietly impact=
 profitability over time.
With that in mind, I spent some time reviewing one of those operational are=
as that tends to drift quietly in the background =97 service pricing. Veter=
inary clinics maintain hundreds of service codes, and unless there is a del=
iberate process to review them regularly, it is very easy for small annual =
adjustments to be missed. Over time this results in pricing gradually falli=
ng behind inflation, which slowly erodes profitability without any single o=
bvious decision causing it.
As part of this review, I=92ve been working with Clinic IQ (software Jack h=
as been developing to help improve operational efficiencies within clinics)=
 around pricing intelligence and operational analytics. Using that system, =
we reviewed the service pricing at Tudor Glen and River Valley to see where=
 this type of drift may have occurred. The system identifies where pricing =
has quietly fallen behind inflation and calculates the appropriate adjustme=
nt. Once identified, those adjustments can be implemented seamlessly and in=
stantly, avoiding the otherwise labour-intensive process of manually review=
ing and correcting hundreds of individual service codes.
The analysis identified the following opportunities:
Tudor Glen
251 service codes below inflation
Estimated annual revenue opportunity: $74,613
River Valley
161 service codes below inflation
Estimated annual revenue opportunity: $27,337
We expect that Rosslyn will show a similar pattern of pricing drift. Access=
 to the Rosslyn system should be available within the next week, at which p=
oint we will run the same analysis. Based on the patterns already identifie=
d, it would not be surprising to find a similar opportunity there, likely i=
n the range of $25,000=96$30,000 in annual revenue improvement once pricing=
 is aligned with inflation.
Combined (including estimated Rosslyn impact)
Estimated annual revenue opportunity: ~$130,000
Importantly, this is not simply a sales increase =97 it represents actual p=
rofit improvement, since the cost of delivering these services does not cha=
nge. To generate the same level of profit through new client growth alone, =
the clinics would likely need to produce approximately $1.3 million in addi=
tional sales.
Most of the recommended adjustments are actually quite modest =97 generally=
 in the range of $3 to $10 per service =97 but because these services are p=
erformed frequently, the cumulative financial impact becomes meaningful.
A few examples include:
=95 Canine wellness exam: +$5.88
=95 Feline wellness exam: +$5.58
=95 Geriatric panel: +$9.00
=95 Blood collection: +$2.94
=95 Radiograph (two views): +$7.02
These adjustments are not significant price increases; they are primarily i=
nflation alignments that would normally have occurred gradually if pricing =
had been reviewed annually.
From a clinic performance perspective, the improvement shows up primarily t=
hrough Per Average Transaction (PAT).
Estimated impact:
=95 Tudor Glen: approximately +$11 PAT per visit
=95 River Valley: approximately +$6 PAT per visit
Importantly, this improvement occurs without requiring any increase in pati=
ent volume.
Within the broader context of the 500 Day Plan, PAT improvement has always =
been one of the key levers available to strengthen clinic profitability. Th=
e estimated impact from this pricing alignment initiative falls directly in=
 line with the PAT improvement targets we previously discussed.
What this exercise also highlighted is that pricing drift is not really a o=
ne-time issue =97 it is something that naturally occurs over time unless th=
ere is a system in place to monitor it.
The Clinic IQ pricing intelligence system was designed to do exactly that b=
y continuously analyzing clinic pricing relative to inflation and service u=
tilization.
Unless there are concerns or alternative suggestions, the next step would b=
e to prepare a service sheet outlining the specific price adjustments ident=
ified by the system and move forward with installing the software required =
to implement those changes efficiently.
If anyone sees a better approach to addressing the issues Blaise raised, or=
 has concerns about moving forward in this way, I would very much welcome t=
hat feedback.
Scott


